A global media company uses AWS Organizations to manage multiple AWS accounts.
Which AWS service or feature can the company use to limit the access to AWS services for member accounts?
Service control policies (SCPs).


The answer is B. Service control policies (SCPs).

Service control policies (SCPs) are a feature of AWS Organizations that can be used to limit the access to AWS services for member accounts. SCPs are attached to organizational units (OUs), and they define the permissions that users and roles in those OUs have to AWS services.

for knowledge
IAM is a service that allows you to create and manage users, groups, and roles. IAM can be used to control access to AWS resources, but it is not specifically designed for limiting access to AWS services.

OUs are a way to organize member accounts in AWS Organizations. OUs do not have any permissions themselves, but they can be used to attach SCPs.

ACLs are used to control access to AWS resources, such as S3 buckets and EC2 instances. ACLs are not used to control access to AWS services.
