A company wants to deploy some of its resources in the AWS Cloud. To meet regulatory requirements, the data must remain local and on premises. There must be low latency between AWS and the company resources.
Which AWS service or feature can be used to meet these requirements?

AWS outpost

One possible AWS service or feature that can be used to meet these requirements is AWS Outposts. AWS Outposts is a fully managed service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to virtually any datacenter, co-location space, or on-premises facility. With AWS Outposts, you can run AWS compute, storage, database, and other services on premises, while seamlessly connecting to the AWS Cloud. This allows you to meet local data residency and low-latency requirements, while benefiting from the agility, scalability, and security of AWS


Another possible AWS service or feature that can be used to meet these requirements is AWS Local Zones. AWS Local Zones are extensions of AWS Regions that are placed closer to population, industry, and IT centers, where you can run latency-sensitive applications using AWS services. AWS Local Zones have a high-bandwidth, low-latency network connection to the parent Region, and support Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS), Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), Amazon Relational Database Service (RDS), and other AWS services. With AWS Local Zones, you can keep your data local and on premises, while accessing the full range of AWS services in the Region2

Note: AWS Outposts allows you to run AWS services on your own premises
but AWS Local Zones allows you to run AWS services in locations that are closer to your end users

so best option is AWS outpost.
