A company is migrating its on-premises database to Amazon RDS. What should the company do to ensure Amazon RDS costs are kept to a minimum?

Right-size before and after migration.

Right-sizing your Amazon RDS instance is the most important thing you can do to keep costs down. When you right-size your instance, you ensure that you are only paying for the resources that you need.

You should right-size your Amazon RDS instance before and after migration. Before migration, you should estimate the resources that your database will need in the cloud. After migration, you should monitor your database usage and adjust the instance size as needed.

and other things that we need to keep in mind during migration to keep the costs at minimum

Tag and track resource utilization: Properly tag your resources and start tracking their utilization. AWS provides the capability to easily tag any of your RDS instances. To do so, locate your instance on the Amazon RDS console. On the Tags tab, add the tags you need to clearly identify the owner of the RDS instance. For more information about tagging, see Tagging Amazon RDS resources. You can add any tags that can help identify your Amazon RDS resources, such as application name and organization group, but the following two tags are recommended: Database owner and Application owner. This information helps quickly identify the owners and alert them about the opportunity for cost-optimization. You donâ€™t need to do anything to track your resource utilization because Amazon RDS automatically sends metrics to Amazon CloudWatch every minute for each active database instance. There are no additional charges for Amazon RDS metrics in CloudWatch. For more information about these metrics, see Overview of monitoring Amazon RDS.

Right-size before and after migration: Right-sizing your Amazon RDS instances can help you save costs. You can use the AWS Trusted Advisor to identify underutilized instances and then resize them to a smaller instance type. For more information, see Resizing your DB instance.

Use Amazon RDS Reserved Instances (RIs): Amazon RDS RIs provide a discounted hourly rate and an optional capacity reservation for EC2 instances. You can choose between three payment options: All Upfront, Partial Upfront, or No Upfront. Depending on which option you choose, you are discounted differently. For more information on how to optimize your Amazon RDS spend, visit the Amazon RDS Cost and Capacity page.

Use Amazon RDS Performance Insights: Amazon RDS Performance Insights is a performance monitoring tool that helps you analyze and troubleshoot the performance of your Amazon RDS instances. It provides a dashboard that displays the performance of your database instance over time. You can use this tool to identify performance bottlenecks and optimize your database instance for better performance.
==================
What is the primary storage service used by Amazon RDS database instances?

Ans:Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store) is a block-level storage service that provides persistent storage for Amazon RDS database instances. EBS volumes are highly durable and scalable, and they can be used to store database data, logs, and backups.

Amazon RDS DB instances use Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volumes for database and log storage 4. Depending on the amount of storage requested, RDS (except for RDS for SQL Server) automatically stripes across multiple Amazon EBS volumes to enhance performance 4.
