=================
Which of the following describes AWS Local Zones?
An extension of an AWS Region to more granular locations
=================

AWS has the following types of locations:

Regions: A region is a self-contained, isolated infrastructure locality. Each region has multiple, isolated locations known as Availability Zones.
Availability Zones: An Availability Zone is an isolated location within a region. Each region has multiple Availability Zones, which are isolated from each other. This allows you to distribute your applications across multiple Availability Zones to improve availability and fault tolerance.
Local Zones: A Local Zone is a type of AWS infrastructure deployment that places compute, storage, database, and other select services closer to end users. Local Zones deliver low latency and high bandwidth to applications that require local data processing, ultra-low latency access to AWS services, or local data storage.
Wavelength Zones: A Wavelength Zone is a specialized type of AWS Local Zone deployed within 5 miles (8 km) of a 5G edge location. Wavelength Zones provide the lowest latency possible between AWS services and on-premises applications and data.
Outposts: An Outpost is a fully managed service that brings native AWS services, infrastructure, and operating models to virtually any data center, co-location space, or on-premises facility. Outposts makes it easy to extend AWS to on-premises environments.
